14. Cassandra: Cassandra Marchese, a lady in waiting to Queen Giovanna at Naples. In the dedication 91 Sannazaro’s Canzoniere she is addressed as ‘una 91 nostro secolo (se io non m’inganno) delle belle eruditissima, delle erudite bellissima’, etc. In one 91 his Epi· grams (iii. 2) she is called ‘quarta Charis, decima Pieris, altera Cypris ’. She was the intimate friend 91 his later years, and he died at her house. It was she who arranged for the first printing of his De Portu Virginis and his Piscatoria (Naples, 1526). [She was married in 1499 to Alionso Castriota, Marquis ο1 Atripalda. But there seems to have been something irregular about the ceremony, and aiter long efforts her husband succeeded in having the contract annulled (1518).
